{"key":"processedPost-10686892","value":{"id":10686892,"first":10684635,"last":10686892,"when":1247754951,"utime":"07/16/09 05:35 PM","content":"Cotton was, and still is used in Asia to seal plastic autoclavable bags.&nbsp; The early bag teks even after the internet came out all had cotton stuffed into the openings on the bags.&nbsp; I agree polyfill is better because it's synthetic, but cotton doesn't automatically contaminate just because it's natural.&nbsp; The cotton gets sterilized along with the substrate, and the part that's exposed to the substrate moisture is on the sterile side.&nbsp; The outside that's exposed to the air dries out.&nbsp; As said, it's still being used today, and the Chinese are supplying 80% of all the shiitake sold in America, so it must work.<br /><br />In line with the modern era, I use filter patch autoclavable bags with a tyvek filter impulse sealed to them from the factory.&nbsp; I get two uses from each bag, which halves the cost.<br />RR","title":"Re: Will cotton work instead of polyfill?"}}